            <ce:sections>
               <ce:section id="sec1" view="all">
                  <ce:label>1</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0030">Introduction</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0025" view="all">Green power and sustainable energy have recently received considerable attentions in human's daily life, wherein a solar-energy material may play an important role for performing photoelectric conversion from the environmental lights (i.e. solar and artificial lights). As an efficient energy material, the compound must have an appropriate band gap close to 1 eV, like CuInSe<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> 
                     <ce:cross-ref refid="bib1" id="crosref0015">[1]</ce:cross-ref>, for effectively absorbing most of the sunlight spectrum. The invention of a new energy material of 1-eV band gap is crucial and essential. The bismuth chalcogenides compounds of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>X<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> (X = S, Se, Te) are generally of a renowned family of thermo-electric materials for thermal-electric power production <ce:cross-ref refid="bib2" id="crosref0020">[2]</ce:cross-ref>. Among the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>X<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> compounds, Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Se<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>, Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Te<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>, and their alloys Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Se<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>-Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Te<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> possess high efficiency of a figure of merit (ZT) from 0.4 to 0.7 at room temperature <ce:cross-refs refid="bib3 bib4 bib5" id="crosrefs0010">[3–5]</ce:cross-refs>, whereas Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> has only a maximum ZT value lower than 0.1 <ce:cross-refs refid="bib6 bib7" id="crosrefs0015">[6,7]</ce:cross-refs>, but it shows nontoxic (green) and low cost (abundant) to be available for renewable energy source applications. Especially, the incorporation of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> into Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Se<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>-Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>Te<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> alloys can improve the ZT value up to a maximum value approaching 1.0 <ce:cross-ref refid="bib2" id="crosref0025">[2]</ce:cross-ref>. The difference between the crystal structures of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> and Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>X<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> (X = Se and Te) may influence the thermo-electric efficiency but the larger band gap of the bismuth sulfide approaching 1 eV <ce:cross-refs refid="bib8 bib9" id="crosrefs0020">[8,9]</ce:cross-refs> can render Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> being used for dual-energy (source) production with thermal electric and solar-energy conversion.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0030" view="all">Moreover the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> usually reveals degenerate <ce:italic>n</ce:italic>-type carrier conduction due to the existence of abundant sulphur vacancies inside the crystal <ce:cross-ref refid="bib10" id="crosref0030">[10]</ce:cross-ref>. The high carrier concentration and high conductivity of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> may degrade the optoelectronic property of the compound. It is inferred that the incorporation of iodine inside the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf> will compensate the sulfur vacancies (i.e. donors) and lower down the conductivity for the improvement of optical-absorption efficiency of the bismuth sulfide. We report, herein, a Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hexagonal pillar crystal that simultaneously possesses an indirect optical gap (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup>) at ∼0.73 eV and a direct gap (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>) at ∼1.06 eV. Temperature-dependent study of the direct and indirect optical gaps shows that the temperature-energy shift of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> is faster than that of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> from 30 to 300 K. The line-width broadening parameter of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> transition in the TR spectra also reveals broadened behavior with respect to the temperature increased from 30 to 300 K. The relatively narrow line width of the TR feature at 30 K verified high crystallinity of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hexagonal pillar crystal.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec2" view="all">
                  <ce:label>2</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0035">Experimental</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0035" view="all">Single crystals of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hexagonal rods were grown by chemical vapor transport (CVT) method. The compounds of the crystals were prepared from the elements Bi: 99.99% pure, S: 99.999% and I: 99.99%. The advantage of using CVT growth is that the crystals can be refined to a highly crystalline atomic arrangement by vapor transfer of the elements, resulting in high crystallinity in the as-grown crystals. In order to achieve stoichiometry, iodine of more mol% in excess was added with respect to the stoichiometric mixture of the constituent elements. Some of iodine was used for compound synthesis, and some of iodine was acted as transport agent. Essentially, the amount of transport agent of I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> was set as 10 mg-cm<ce:sup loc="post">−3</ce:sup>, so the stoichiometric weighting of other iodine element was used for crystal growth of the Bi1<ce:inf loc="post">3</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. The good crystalline quality of the CVT-grown crystals using I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> as the transport agent was also found by previous as-grown GeS crystal <ce:cross-ref refid="bib11" id="crosref0035">[11]</ce:cross-ref>. In this experiment, totally about 12 g of the elements were introduced into a quartz ampoule (22 mm OD, 17 mm ID, 20 cm length), which was then cooled with liquid nitrogen, evacuated to 10<ce:sup loc="post">−6</ce:sup> Torr and sealed <ce:cross-ref refid="bib12" id="crosref0040">[12]</ce:cross-ref>. The mixture was slowly heated to 600 °C and maintained for two days. The temperature was then set as 600 °C (heating zone) → 550 °C (growth zone) with a gradient of −2.5 °C/cm in a horizontal tube furnace. The reaction kept 240 h for producing large single crystals. After the growth, the as-grown Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> crystals show black-shiny surface and a rod-shape outline with a diameter about hundreds nm to hundreds μm. The stoichiometry of the as-grown crystal was determined by energy dispersive X-ray (EDX) and the stoichiometric composition is determined to be Bi<ce:inf loc="post">12.667</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> ≈ Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. The TR experiments were carried out using indirect heating manner with a gold-evaporated quartz plate as the heating element <ce:cross-ref refid="bib13" id="crosref0045">[13]</ce:cross-ref>. A 150 W tungsten halogen lamp dispersed by a PTI 0.2-m monochromator provided the monochromatic light. An InGaAs photodetector acted as the detection unit. The polished sheet-type sample with shiny surface was closely attached on the heating element by silicone grease. The on-off heating disturbance was necessary to avoid any increase of temperature on sample. A closed-cycle cryogenic refrigerator with a thermometer controller facilitated the temperature-dependent measurements from low to room temperature. Measurements of the reflectivity and transmission at near-normal incidence were made on the same monochromatic system as TR. Transmission intensity was closely monitored to obtain an incidence as close to 90° as possible. Measurements were made at several temperatures between 30 and 300 K with a temperature stability of 0.5 K or better.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec3" role="results" view="all">
                  <ce:label>3</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0040">Results and discussions</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0040" view="all">
                     <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0050">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig1"/>(a) shows the as-grown single crystals of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> inside two different sealed quartz tubes. They are essentially rod and pillar shape crystals with obvious <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> axial direction [i.e. the hexagonal lattice's <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> axis] and black shiny surface. The outline of the crystal is an octahedron (hexagonal rod) that owns a width from hundreds nm to hundreds μm and a length from hundreds μm to several mm. Orientation-dependent X-ray diffraction (XRD) measurements of the pillar-type crystals are carried out to evaluate the structure and crystalline phase of the as-grown Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0055">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>(b) shows the XRD patterns of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hexagonal rod crystal with different X-ray incidence directions of <ce:bold>
                        <ce:italic>k</ce:italic>
                     </ce:bold> ⊥ <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> (A, upper spectrum) and <ce:bold>
                        <ce:italic>k</ce:italic>
                     </ce:bold> || <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> (B, lower spectrum) done on the m plane. The representation scheme of m plane and <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> plane is shown in the lower inset of <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0060">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>(b). The electron diffraction pattern (EDP) of the <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> plane is also included for verification of the hexagonal phase. As shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0065">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>(b), several indexed peaks of (300), (130), (401), (520), (621), and (721) planes that agree with hexagonal Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> 
                     <ce:cross-refs refid="bib14 bib15" id="crosrefs0025">[14,15]</ce:cross-refs> can be clearly detected in the XRD pattern with <ce:bold>
                        <ce:italic>k</ce:italic>
                     </ce:bold> ⊥ <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> (A) condition. Especially, three specific peaks of (300), (130) and (520) in A are undetectable in the XRD pattern of the <ce:bold>
                        <ce:italic>k</ce:italic>
                     </ce:bold> || <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> spectrum in B [see red-dashed arrow lines]. It is owing to the (300), (130) and (520) planes are parallel to the <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> axis of the crystal and the diffraction peaks cannot appear in the <ce:bold>
                        <ce:italic>k</ce:italic>
                     </ce:bold> || <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> condition. This result verifies the structural anisotropy of the as-grown Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hexagonal pillar. From <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0070">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>(b), the lattice constant of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> can be determined to be <ce:italic>a</ce:italic> = 15.71 Å and <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> = 4.02 Å. In usual, the shorter lattice constant (<ce:italic>c</ce:italic> axis) could result in relative stronger bond strength with respect to the other (<ce:italic>a</ce:italic>) axis. The morphological outline of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> hence tends to be a long hexagonal rod along <ce:italic>c</ce:italic> axis as shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig1" id="crosref0075">Fig. 1</ce:cross-ref>(a). The XRD result, lattice constants and rod-shape morphology of the crystals also resemble with a previous Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> compound grown from surfur/iodine flux mixture <ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0080">[16]</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0045" view="all">To evaluate the band-edge property of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> semiconductor, transmission measurements at near normal incidence are implemented from 30 to 300 K. The absorption coefficient α was determined from the transmittance T by taking into account the spectral dependence of reflectance R using the relation <mml:math altimg="si1.gif" overflow="scroll">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mtext>T</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">=</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>[</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">−</mml:mi>
                              <mml:msup>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtext>R</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:msup>
                              <mml:mtext>exp</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">−α</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:msup>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>[</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mtext>1</mml:mtext>
                                    <mml:mo>-</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mtext>R</mml:mtext>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              </mml:msup>
                              <mml:mtext>exp</mml:mtext>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">−</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">α</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mi mathvariant="italic">d</mml:mi>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>]</mml:mo>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, where <ce:italic>d</ce:italic> is the sample thickness. <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0085">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig2"/>(a) displays the absorption coefficient as a function of photon energy as determined for the m-plane Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> between 30 and 300 K. As the general semiconductor behavior, the absorption edge shifts to higher energies as the temperature of the sample is lowered. From the analysis of the experimental data, the absorption coefficient α is found to be proportional to (hν-E<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf>)<ce:sup loc="post">n</ce:sup> with n = 2 ± 0.1. This suggests an indirect allowed transition for materials <ce:cross-ref refid="bib17" id="crosref0090">[17]</ce:cross-ref>. For an indirect allowed transition, the absorption coefficient α for a single phonon process can be expressed as <ce:cross-ref refid="bib17" id="crosref0095">[17]</ce:cross-ref>:<ce:display>
                        <ce:formula id="fd1">
                           <ce:label>(1)</ce:label>
                           <mml:math display="block" altimg="si2.gif" overflow="scroll">
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi>α</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>h</mml:mtext>
                                 <mml:mi>ν</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>=</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mfrac>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mtext>A</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:msup>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mtext>h</mml:mtext>
                                                   <mml:mi>ν</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo>-</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mtext>g</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                      <mml:mtext>P</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:msub>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:msup>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mtext>exp</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                <mml:mtext>P</mml:mtext>
                                             </mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mtext>kT</mml:mtext>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mfrac>
                                 <mml:mo>+</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mfrac>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mtext>B</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:msup>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                                <mml:mrow>
                                                   <mml:mtext>h</mml:mtext>
                                                   <mml:mi>ν</mml:mi>
                                                   <mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mrow>
                                                         <mml:mo>-</mml:mo>
                                                         <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                      </mml:mrow>
                                                      <mml:mtext>g</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:msub>
                                                   <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                                   <mml:msub>
                                                      <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                      <mml:mtext>P</mml:mtext>
                                                   </mml:msub>
                                                </mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mn>2</mml:mn>
                                       </mml:msup>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>exp</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:msub>
                                                <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                                <mml:mtext>P</mml:mtext>
                                             </mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                             <mml:mtext>kT</mml:mtext>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mfrac>
                                 <mml:mtext>,</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:math>
                        </ce:formula>
                     </ce:display>where hν is the energy of the incident photon, E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> the band gap, E<ce:inf loc="post">p</ce:inf> the energy of phonon assisting the transition, and A and B are constants. The first term on the right hand side of Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd1" id="crosref0100">(1)</ce:cross-ref> corresponds to absorption of a photon and a phonon, whereas the second term corresponds to absorption of a photon and emission of a phonon and contributes only for hν ≥ E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> + E<ce:inf loc="post">p</ce:inf>. The αh<ce:italic>ν</ce:italic> data of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> at different temperatures are then fitted to Eq. <ce:cross-ref refid="fd1" id="crosref0105">(1)</ce:cross-ref> and representative results are shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0110">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>(b). Where the averaged phonon energy E<ce:inf loc="post">p</ce:inf> is about 0.03 eV at each temperature and the obtained band gap E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> at different temperatures are depicted in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0115">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig3"/>(b) for comparison. The analysis of band gap in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0120">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>(b) indicates that Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> is an indirect semiconductor in which a single phonon makes important contribution in assisting indirect transition. The indirect gap (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup>) of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> from the analysis in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig2" id="crosref0125">Fig. 2</ce:cross-ref>(b) is determined to be 0.73 ± 0.03 eV at 300 K.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0050" view="all">To further characterize the direct band gap of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>, TR measurements are carried out. TR has proven to be a very powerful tool for evaluation of direct interband transitions <ce:cross-ref refid="bib18" id="crosref0130">[18]</ce:cross-ref>. The derivative spectral line shape of the transition feature enhances the ability to determine exact energy location of the direct transition. Shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0135">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(a) are the representative temperature-dependent TR spectra of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> in the temperature range between 30 and 300 K. The dashed lines are the experimental data and solid lines are the least-square fits to the first derivative Lorentzian line-shape function appropriate for interband transition expressed as <ce:cross-ref refid="bib19" id="crosref0140">[19]</ce:cross-ref>: <mml:math altimg="si3.gif" overflow="scroll">
                        <mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Δ</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mtext>R</mml:mtext>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mtext>R</mml:mtext>
                           </mml:mrow>
                           <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">=</mml:mi>
                           <mml:mtext>Re</mml:mtext>
                           <mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo>[</mml:mo>
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mo>∑</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                                 <mml:mo>·</mml:mo>
                                 <mml:msup>
                                    <mml:mi>e</mml:mi>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mtext>φ</mml:mtext>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:msup>
                                 <mml:msup>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">−</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:msubsup>
                                          <mml:mtext>E</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mtext>g</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mtext>d</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:msubsup>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">+</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>j</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mi>Γ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>−</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mi>m</mml:mi>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:msup>
                              </mml:mrow>
                              <mml:mo>]</mml:mo>
                           </mml:mrow>
                        </mml:mrow>
                     </mml:math>, where <mml:math altimg="si4.gif" overflow="scroll">
                        <mml:mi>A</mml:mi>
                     </mml:math> and <mml:math altimg="si5.gif" overflow="scroll">
                        <mml:mtext>φ</mml:mtext>
                     </mml:math> are the amplitude and phase of the line shape, and E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> and Γ are the energy and broadening parameter of the interband transition. The value of <ce:italic>m</ce:italic> = 0.5 is used for the first derivative line shape analysis of critical-point transition of direct band gap for Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. The obtained transition energies of direct gap E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> are shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0145">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b) together with those of the indirect gaps E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> by absorption are also included for comparison. It is clear that the value of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> is lower than E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> at each temperature. This result sustains indirect band edge for Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. Previous report on the edge characteristics of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> band also showed that there is a lower indirect (∼0.3 eV) and higher direct (∼0.9 eV) bandgap from the diffused-reflectance edge and band calculations <ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0150">[16]</ce:cross-ref>. However, for the determination of bandgap, optical absorption by light transmission is more accurate than reflectance experiment and the direct gap measured by TR is also more reliable. Furthermore, the resistivity of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> rod is about 1.1 × 10<ce:sup loc="post">3</ce:sup> Ω-cm at 300 K. The high resistivity of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> means that the bandgap of the rod is not less than 0.3 eV. The residual absorption below 0.73 to 0.3 eV by diffused reflectance <ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0155">[16]</ce:cross-ref> is maybe due to impurity contribution. In this optical study, the value of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> is hence determined to be ∼0.73 eV and that of direct E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> is ∼1.06 eV as shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0160">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b). According to band calculation, the conduction-band minimum is constructed by bismuth dimmer by Bi<ce:sup loc="post">4+</ce:sup> &amp; Bi<ce:sup loc="post">3+</ce:sup> and the valence-band maximum is dominated by iodine states <ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0165">[16]</ce:cross-ref>. The direct gap E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> is from the valence-band maximum to the conduction band with Γ→Γ transition. The indirect E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> transition may come from the valence-band maximum at Γ to the conduction-band minimum at other <ce:italic>k</ce:italic> direction (e.g. L point) that consisted in the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> band structure <ce:cross-ref refid="bib16" id="crosref0170">[16]</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0055" view="all">The temperature dependences of direct and indirect band gaps of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> can be further analyzed by using a Varshni empirical relationship as E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> (T) = E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> (0) - a⋅T<ce:sup loc="post">2</ce:sup>/(b + T) <ce:cross-ref refid="bib20" id="crosref0175">[20]</ce:cross-ref>, where E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> (0) is the band gap at absolute zero, a is related to the electron-phonon interaction, and b is closely correlated with Debye temperature. The fitting results for the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> and E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> are shown by solid lines in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0180">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b). The obtained fitting parameters for E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>) are E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf> (0) = 0.925 ± 0.004 (1.157 ± 0.003) eV, a = 0.93 ± 0.08 (0.48 ± 0.04) meV/K, and b = 120 ± 60 (120 ± 40) K, respectively. The values of Debye temperature related parameter b are similar for both E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> and E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> in the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>, whereas the electron-phonon interaction parameter a of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> is much larger than that of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>. It means that the temperature-energy shift of E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> is faster than that of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> as displayed in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0185">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b). It is a general character for an indirect semiconductor that simultaneously possesses direct and indirect gaps and we will discuss this behavior later. The obtained fitting parameters in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0190">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b) can be the estimation of band gaps when the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> semiconductor operated at higher temperature region above 300 K. As shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0195">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b), the averaged value of bandgap (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> and E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>) is about 0.9 eV at 300 K and it will increase to about 1.0 eV at 77 K. The optical absorption and photoelectric conversion efficiency can be enhanced at the liquid-nitrogen temperature for the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> semiconductor rod. The presence of indirect and direct bandgaps in Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> also can increase the absorption energy range to improve photoelectric energy conversion.</ce:para>
                  <ce:para id="p0060" view="all">As shown in the temperature-dependent TR spectra of <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0200">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(a), the line width Γ (half width at half maximum, HWHM) of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> feature increases with the temperature is increased from 30 to 300 K. The relative smaller HWHM (∼79 meV) at 30 K as well as broadened behavior with the increase of the temperatures from 30 to 300 K indicated that good crystallinity of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> semiconductor. The experimental values of Γ obtained from the Lorentzian line-shape fits of the TR spectra are shown in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0205">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>
                     <ce:float-anchor refid="fig4"/> with representative error bars. The solid curve is the least-square fit by an expression proposed for the line-width analysis as <ce:cross-ref refid="bib21" id="crosref0210">[21]</ce:cross-ref>:<ce:display>
                        <ce:formula id="fd2">
                           <ce:label>(2)</ce:label>
                           <mml:math display="block" altimg="si6.gif" overflow="scroll">
                              <mml:mrow>
                                 <mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Γ</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:mtext>T</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">=</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Γ</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mtext>0</mml:mtext>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">+</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">Γ</mml:mi>
                                          <mml:mrow>
                                             <mml:mtext>LO</mml:mtext>
                                          </mml:mrow>
                                       </mml:msub>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                    <mml:mo>/</mml:mo>
                                    <mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mo>[</mml:mo>
                                       <mml:mtext>exp</mml:mtext>
                                       <mml:mrow>
                                          <mml:mo>(</mml:mo>
                                          <mml:msub>
                                             <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">θ</mml:mi>
                                             <mml:mrow>
                                                <mml:mtext>LO</mml:mtext>
                                             </mml:mrow>
                                          </mml:msub>
                                          <mml:mtext>/T</mml:mtext>
                                          <mml:mo>)</mml:mo>
                                       </mml:mrow>
                                       <mml:mi mathvariant="normal">−</mml:mi>
                                       <mml:mn>1</mml:mn>
                                       <mml:mo>]</mml:mo>
                                    </mml:mrow>
                                 </mml:mrow>
                              </mml:mrow>
                           </mml:math>
                        </ce:formula>
                     </ce:display>where Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf>, zero-temperature broadening parameter, is temperature independent and which is invoked from the mechanisms of impurity, dislocation, electron interaction and Auger processes. The Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> is caused by electron (exciton)-LO phonon (Frohlich) interaction and θ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> is the LO phonon temperature <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0215">[22]</ce:cross-ref>. The obtained values of fitting parameters are Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf> = 80 ± 9 meV, Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> = 410 ± 140 meV, and θ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> = 370 ± 100 K, respectively. The values of Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf> and Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> are larger than those of Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf> = 18.3 ± 1.0 meV, Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> = 77 ± 20 meV in MoS<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> 
                     <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0220">[22]</ce:cross-ref>, and Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf> ≈ 23 meV, Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> ≈ 46 meV in GaAs <ce:cross-ref refid="bib22" id="crosref0225">[22]</ce:cross-ref>, respectively. The smaller value of Γ<ce:inf loc="post">0</ce:inf> means the binary MoS<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> and III-V GaAs possess an even better crystallinity than that of as-grown ternary Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> crystal. The reason is the bismuth sulfide iodide belonging to a group V-VI-VII compound, where the misvalency between the incorporated elements is easy to form defective sites like vacancy and interstitial in the crystal. It is different from that of the other match-valence compound like III-V GaAs with a good valency. Furthermore, the larger value of Γ<ce:inf loc="post">LO</ce:inf> of the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> will broaden the line width of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> feature rapidly from 30 to 300 K. This phenomenon can be evident in <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0230">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(a) and <ce:cross-ref refid="fig4" id="crosref0235">Fig. 4</ce:cross-ref>. This result will also push the temperature-energy shift of the indirect gap E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> varies faster than that of the direct gap E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>. When the temperature is raised up, the enhancement of thermal broadening of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> feature causes faster shift of the indirect absorption tail for the Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf>. This result can be observed and evident in the analysis of <ce:cross-ref refid="fig3" id="crosref0240">Fig. 3</ce:cross-ref>(b). The faster shift of absorption tail can be a general character of a semiconductor that simultaneously possessing direct and indirect band edges, like ReS<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> and ReSe<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf> layered semiconductors <ce:cross-ref refid="bib23" id="crosref0245">[23]</ce:cross-ref>.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
               <ce:section id="sec4" role="conclusion" view="all">
                  <ce:label>4</ce:label>
                  <ce:section-title id="sectitle0045">Conclusion</ce:section-title>
                  <ce:para id="p0065" view="all">In conclusion, the optical band-edge property of a hexagonal Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> has been evaluated by temperature-dependent absorption and TR measurements in the temperature range between 30 and 300 K. Absorption measurement characterizes its indirect band edge (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup>) and TR measurement probes its direct optical gap (E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup>). The temperature-energy shift of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">ind</ce:sup> shows faster variation than that of the E<ce:inf loc="post">g</ce:inf>
                     <ce:sup loc="post">d</ce:sup> owing to the rapidly thermal broadening of direct gap causes rapid shift of the absorption tail. The indirect and direct band gaps of Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> are determined to be ∼0.73 eV and ∼1.06 eV at room temperature. The averaged value of optical gap close to 1 eV renders this new Bi<ce:inf loc="post">13</ce:inf>I<ce:inf loc="post">2</ce:inf>S<ce:inf loc="post">18</ce:inf> semiconductor being a promising candidate available for solar-energy absorption and NIR photodetection.</ce:para>
               </ce:section>
            </ce:sections>
